learning_outcomes_text:
"Students have a working knowledge of
(a) the fundamental definitions pertaining to sets, relations, functions, orderings, graphs, and trees;
(b) the fundamental data structures (such as heaps, hash tables, and binary search trees), basic sorting algorithms (such as MergeSort and QuickSort), and basic graph algorithms (such as minimum spanning trees, breadth- and depth-first search), and know their basic properties;
(c) the formal definitions of various notions of automata (deterministic and non-deterministic finite automata, push-down automata, and Turing machines), various classes of formal languages (regular, context-free, decidable, undecidable), and various complexity classes of computational problems (P, NP, NP-hard, NP-complete, undecidable);
(d) the definitions of cuts and flows in graphs, the concept of a greedy choice property and optimal substructure in an optimization problem.","Students can
(a) formalize statements in first-order predicate logic, are skilled in proving formal statements using standard proof techniques (e.g., proof by contradiction, case distinction, induction, double counting, using invariants), and can apply those techniques to establish the correctness of algorithms;
(b) apply basic algorithm design techniques (incremental, recursive, divide-and-conquer);
(c) use pumping lemmas to establish that a language is not regular or context-free, can prove the equivalence of automata, and prove that a computational problem is undecidable or NP-hard by a reduction;
(d) use more advanced algorithm design techniques (backtracking, greedy algorithm, dynamic programming) to solve optimization problems and use advanced graph algorithms (shortest paths, maximum flows) to solve other computational problems; and
(e) prove the correctness of algorithms thus developed and can characterize their efficiency by performing a worst-case asymptotic analysis.",Students can effectively communicate to peers about topics in theoretical computer science (e.g., algorithms, automata, grammars, formal syntax) and support their claims with mathematical proofs.,After completing the learning line, students have a systematic, formal approach to solving computational problems. They aim to solve computational problems by designing solutions that are provably correct and efficient and reflect on the limitations of their solutions.

